\id XXA - Aboriginal Plain English Version
\is1 About this translation
\ip This booklet uses the \bdit Plain English Version\bdit* (PEV) of the Scriptures, an English translation of the Bible designed for Indigenous Australians whose first language is an Indigenous language. Its purpose is to convey the meaning of the original Scripture in English that is easy to understand and natural for them. We have, as much as possible, limited its grammar, semantic and rhetorical features to those common in Aboriginal languages, and its vocabulary to the English that is most widely used.
\ip We have applied the principles of meaning-based translation, wherein we have sought to convey the same meaning that the original authors conveyed to the original readers. That means not just considering individual words, but also the message of the whole passage.
\ip The following are some of the more common modifications that have been made:
\ili1 • Where the grammar of the original has used the passive voice, we have used the active voice, since the grammars of most indigenous Australian languages do not have passive voice.
\ili1 • Where the original text has used an abstract noun to express a concept that is fundamentally an action or a quality, we have usually used a verb or adjective to translate that concept, since abstract nouns are comparatively rare in Australian languages.
\ili1 • Where the grammar of the original has used long and complicated sentences, we have conformed to the grammars of Australian languages by using shorter sentences, making other adjustments as necessary to retain the meaning carried by the grammar of the original.
\ili1 • Where the original text has implicit or background information that would not be obvious to our target audience, we have made that information explicit.
\ili1 • Where the original text has used a word or phrase, the literal translation of which would not be understood by our target audience, we have used an explanatory rendering to convey the same meaning, whether or not it involved more words.
\ili1 • Where the original text has used figurative language that would be taken as literal by our target audience, we have stated the meaning of the figure rather than its literal form.
\ili1 • Where the original text is not in chronological or logical order, we have usually adjusted the order of information.
\im At any one place in our translation we may have used a combination of the above.
\im \sig PEV Translation Team \sig* 
